  "body": "Not copying function arguments into allocas prevents certain\noptimizations from happening, for example SROA splitting aggregates into\ntheir scalar components.\n\nFor example this function:\n\n```\nstruct S { x: i64, y: i64, z: Box<i64> }\n\nfn test(s: S) -> S {\n  let s = s;\n  let s = s;\n  let s = s;\n  s\n}\n```\n\nCurrently isn't optimized down to a single memcpy, but it is optimized\nto that with this change.\n\nTo get the full effect, we also need to stop marking the argument as\ndead (lifetime.end intrinsic) after copying it into the alloca, because\nthat also stops certain optimizations from happening. Dropping that\nintrinsic comes without negative side effects, as non-allocas don't\nparticipate in stack coloring anyway.\n",
